ZALE CORPORATION By: Counsel for Respondent Page 7 of 7 MATTHEW D. GOLD Counsel for the Federal Trade Commission APPROVED: JEFFREY KLURFELD Regional Director San Francisco Regional Office Page 8 of 7 APPENDIX A Your Guide to Pearls Natural Pearls A pearl formed in the wild by the random intrusion of a natural irritant into a mollusk shell, without s the intervention of man.
There are few natural pearls on the general consumer jewelry market today.
Cultured Pearls A cultured pearl is also grown by nature but with the assistance of man.
This patented process involves the insertion of a "nucleus" into the oyster.
The oyster is then carefully nurtured for the desired type of pearl.
The quality of cultured pearls varies and is judged by the pearls lustre, surface, shape, color and size.
Imitation Pearls A manufactured product composed of any material or materials that simulate in appearance a natural pearl or cultured pearl.
